  array('id' => '791','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Marcus Gayle','dob' => '1970-09-27','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Marcus Anthony Gayle (born 27 September 1970, Hammersmith, London) is an English born Jamaican former professional footballer, who is now manager of Staines Town. Gayle\\\'s primary position was as a striker but also played as a winger and central defender towards the end of his career. His most notable clubs included Wimbledon and Watford before he finished his playing career at AFC Wimbledon. He won 14 caps for Jamaica and was a key player for his country at the 1998 World Cup tournament.

After retiring as a player, he became manager of the AFC Wimbledon reserve team for three years before taking charge of Staines Town in 2012.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 11:24:03','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'marcus-gayle'),
  array('id' => '792','region_id' => '17,2','title' => 'Marcus Patrick','dob' => '1974-06-05','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Actors','description' => 'Marcus Patrick (born Patrick Marcus Osborne, 5 June 1974, Bath, Somerset) is an English actor.  Mother is Jamaican, Cuban and Cherokee. My father is English, Irish, and French. My dad was always obsessed with black women.  He is an actor and producer, known for Descent (2007), Violet Tendencies (2010) and I Do... I Did! (2009).','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => 'Actor,','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '2015-04-21','createdate' => '2014-07-06 11:28:55','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'marcus-patrick'),
  array('id' => '793','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Marlon King','dob' => '1980-04-26','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Athletes','description' => 'Marlon Francis King (born 26 April 1980) is a professional footballer who plays as a striker. He is currently serving an 18-month jail sentence following a conviction for dangerous driving in May 2014.[2]

Born in Dulwich, London he started his career in non-League football with Dulwich Hamlet, he played for Barnet, Gillingham, Leeds United and Nottingham Forest before moving to Watford in 2005. At Watford he was the Football League Championship top scorer, and was voted Watford player of the season as the club earned promotion to the Premier League. King joined Wigan Athletic in 2008, and subsequently spent loan spells at Hull City and Middlesbrough. He joined Coventry City in September 2010, following his release from prison, and made 29 appearances for the club before controversially switching to Birmingham City in June 2011. He made 79 appearances for Birmingham, before suffering a series of injuries during the 2012–13 season that prevented him from playing again, leaving the club in August 2013 by mutual consent. King has also played and scored for the Jamaican national team.
In 2004 King played an important part in Jamaica\\\'s unsuccessful attempt to qualify for the 2006 World Cup, scoring six goals in eight games. He played for Jamaica in the friendly against Ghana on 29 May 2006 which they lost 4–1.[49] He was named in the squad to face England in a friendly on 3 June 2006, but was sent home for an alleged breach of discipline. Jamaica lost the match 6–0.[50]

As a result of the incident, the Jamaican Football Federation banned King from international football until May 2008. When Captain Horace Burrell returned as the JFF president he lifted the ban.[51] King played in Jamaica\\\'s 1–1 draw with Costa Rica in February 2008, where he provided the cross for Jamaica\\\'s goal. King also played for Jamaica in a friendly against Trinidad and Tobago scoring a goal and captaining the team in the absence of Ricardo Gardner due to injury','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => 'soccer, striker,  ','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '2015-04-26','createdate' => '2014-07-06 11:31:17','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'marlon-king'),
  array('id' => '794','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Mary Seacole','dob' => '0000-00-00','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Mary Jane Seacole (1805 – 14 May 1881), n&eacute;e Grant,[1][2] was a Jamaican-born woman of Scottish and Creole descent who set up a \\\'British Hotel\\\' behind the lines during the Crimean War, which she described as \\&quot;a mess-table and comfortable quarters for sick and convalescent officers,\\&quot; and provided succour for wounded servicemen on the battlefield.[2] She was posthumously awarded the Jamaican Order of Merit in 1991. In 2004 she was voted the greatest black Briton.[3]

She acquired knowledge of herbal medicine in the Caribbean. When the Crimean War broke out, she applied to the War Office to assist but was refused. She travelled independently and set up her hotel and assisted battlefield wounded. She became extremely popular among service personnel who raised money for her when she faced destitution after the war.

After her death, she was forgotten for almost a century, but today is celebrated as a woman who successfully combatted racial prejudice.[4] Her autobiography, Wonderful Adventures of Mrs. Seacole in Many Lands (1857), is one of the earliest autobiographies of a mixed-race woman, although some aspects of its accuracy have been questioned. It has been claimed that Seacole\\\'s achievements have been exaggerated for political reasons[5] and a plan to erect a statue of her at St Thomas\\\' Hospital, London, describing her as a \\&quot;pioneer nurse\\&quot;,[6] has generated controversy.[7][8] Further controversy broke out in the United Kingdom late in 2012 over reports of a proposal to remove her from the country\\\'s National Curriculum.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 11:34:05','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'mary-seacole'),
  array('id' => '795','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Maxi Priest','dob' => '1961-06-10','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Singer','description' => 'Max Alfred &quot;Maxi&quot; Elliott (born 10 June 1961), known as Maxi Priest, is a British reggae vocalist of Jamaican descent. He is best known for singing reggae music with an R&amp;B influence, otherwise known as reggae fusion, and became one of the first international successes who regularly dabbled in the genre and one of the most successful reggae fusion acts of all-time. His music is sometimes closer to R&amp;B, and pop, than to reggae music itself. His cousin, Jacob Miller, a reggae icon, was the frontman in the popular reggae group Inner Circle.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => 'singer, dancehall, reggae, ','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '2015-04-21','createdate' => '2014-07-06 11:36:50','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'maxi-priest'),
  array('id' => '796','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Mel Gaynor','dob' => '1956-05-29','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Musician','description' => 'Mel George Gaynor (born 29 May 1959, Balham, London, England[1]) is a British musician. He is best known as the longtime drummer for the rock band, Simple Minds.[2] Gaynor was born to a Jamaican father and an Afro-Brazilian mother.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => 'drummer, Simple Minds,musician ','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '2015-04-21','createdate' => '2014-07-06 11:38:08','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'mel-gaynor'),
  array('id' => '797','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Melissa Bel','dob' => '1964-03-05','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Melissa Cecelia Ewen Bell (born 5 March 1964) is the former lead singer of Grammy winning R&amp;B act Soul II Soul, and currently fronts the group Soul Explosion, which started in 1999. She has also worked with Liza Minnelli, Whitney Houston, and Stevie Wonder.[1] Bell is the mother of singer Alexandra Burke; her other children are Sheneice, David, and Aaron.[2] Her late father, Ivan, was of Afro-Jamaican descent and her mother was of Dougla descent. In September 2009, Burke accused her mother of jealousy following her success on The X Factor. Bell fought back, stating: \\&quot;What type of mum is jealous of her daughter? She doesn\\\'t have millions but when she does she\\\'ll look after me. If she gets the best then I get the best and getting my life-saving treatment - that\\\'s my priority\\&quot;.[5]','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 11:40:43','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'melissa-bel'),
