  array('id' => '812','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Nyron Nosworthy','dob' => '1980-10-11','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Nyron Paul Henry Nosworthy (born 11 October 1980) is a professional footballer who last played for Watford as a defender. Prior to joining Watford in 2012, he played for Sunderland in the Premier League.Nosworthy stated his ambitions to play international football for Jamaica, his father\\\'s country.[3] He was also eligible to play for Guyana through his mother.[19] He is a strong supporter of Arsenal.[20] On 4 October 2007 Nosworthy received his first call-up to the full Jamaica squad for their games against Ghana and Honduras.[21] Nosworthy received another call up to Jamaica\\\'s international team in May 2012 along with teammate Adrian Mariappa.[22] He made his international debut for Jamaica against Guyana on 19 May 2012. Nosworthy scored his first goal for Jamaica in a World Cup qualifier against Antigua and Barbuda, Jamaica won the game 4–1.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 17:54:49','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'nyron-nosworthy'),
  array('id' => '813','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Omar Lye-Fook','dob' => '1968-10-14','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Omar Christopher Lye-Fook MBE (born 14 October 1968, London[1]), known professionally as Omar, is a British soul singer, songwriter and musician. Omar grew up in Canterbury, Kent. He learned his craft classically, playing the trumpet, piano and percussion. He also spent two years at Chetham\\\'s School of Music in Manchester, and the Guildhall School of Music in London. His most well-known song was his debut single \\&quot;There\\\'s Nothing Like This\\&quot;.[1] It reached number 14 in the UK Singles Chart on re-release in 1991.[2] Allmusic noted that he is described by some as the father of British neo soul.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 17:58:35','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'omar-lye-fook'),
  array('id' => '814','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Paul Hall','dob' => '1972-07-03','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Paul Anthony Hall (born 3 July 1972 in Manchester, England), is a retired English-born Jamaican international footballer. He is currently a coach at Conference National side Tamworth, during his career, Hall was a striker who could also play on the right wing.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:01:35','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'paul-hall'),
  array('id' => '815','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Ranking Miss P','dob' => '0000-00-00','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Ranking Miss P is a British radio presenter, born in London to Jamaican parents.

After leaving school, Miss P was studying to become a teacher, but instead was persuaded by her brother DJ Lepke to start broadcasting on his community radio station, Dread Broadcasting Corporation (DBC), the first black station in Europe.

In 1983, Miss P was approached by BBC Television to compose and perform visual promotional trails and the theme song for their weekly magazine programme Ebony.

On 31 March 1985 she began presenting a weekly reggae show on BBC Radio 1 on Sunday nights. It was Radio 1\\\'s first ever show dedicated solely to reggae music, and Miss P was one of the station\\\'s first black presenters.

She went on to present a programme called Riddim and Blues on BBC London 94.9 on Saturday nights, in which she played a wide variety of black music. She has two sons and a daughter.

Both DJ Lepke (real name Leroy Anderson) and Ranking Miss P are the younger siblings of Bob Marley\\\'s wife Rita Marley.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:05:04','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'ranking-miss-p'),
  array('id' => '816','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Rendall Munroe','dob' => '1980-06-01','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Athletes','description' => 'Rendall Munroe (born 1 June 1980 in Leicester, England) is an English super bantamweight boxer. Munroe currently resides in Leicester and is the WBA International Super Bantamweight champion. He is also a former holder of the EBU and Commonwealth Super Bantamweight titles. His dayjob as a binman is well publicised as his nickname is \\\'The Boxing Binman\\\'. He and his corner men also come out wearing fluorescent yellow binman jackets. Munroe attended English Martyrs Catholic School. rubbish runs in the family, although his old man actually isn\\\'t a dustman; Munroe\\\'s Jamaican-born dad Alan is a road sweeper. &quot;He always said to me as a kid: \\\'You\\\'re not going out to hang out on the streets, do something constructive\\\', says Munroe. &quot;And here I am now cleaningup the town just like him!&quot;','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => 'boxer, super bantamweight, champion, ','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '2015-04-21','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:08:06','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'rendall-munroe'),
  array('id' => '817','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Richard Langley','dob' => '1979-12-27','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Richard Barrington Michael Langley (born 27 December 1979) is an English born-Jamaican footballer who most recently played for Conference South side Staines Town. Langley signed for Marcus Gayle\\\'s side having started the season at Hemel Hempstead Town. Prior to his spell in Hertfordshire, Langley played for Thai Premier League side Pattaya United before leaving them at the turn of the year. He has previously played for Queens Park Rangers (during two spells), Cardiff City and Luton Town and has been capped by Jamaica.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:12:19','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'richard-langley'),
  array('id' => '818','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Richard Reid "Shoe Bomber"','dob' => '1973-08-12','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Terrorist','description' => 'Richard Colvin Reid (born 12 August 1973), also known as the Shoe Bomber, is an Englishman who attempted to detonate explosives packed into the shoes he was wearing, while on American Airlines Flight 63 from Paris to Miami. Born to a father who was a career criminal, Reid converted to Islam as a young man in prison after years as a petty criminal himself. Later he became \\"radicalized\\" and went to Pakistan and Afghanistan, where he trained and became a member of al-Qaeda.

On 22 December 2001, he boarded American Airlines Flight 63 between Paris and Miami, wearing shoes packed with explosives, which he unsuccessfully tried to detonate. Passengers subdued him on the plane, which landed at Logan International Airport in Boston, Massachusetts, the closest US airport. He was subsequently arrested and indicted. In 2002, Reid pleaded guilty in U.S. federal court to eight criminal counts of terrorism, based on his attempt to destroy a commercial aircraft in flight. He was sentenced to life in prison without parole and is held in a super maximum security prison in the United States.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => 'Terrorist, ','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '2015-05-02','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:15:44','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'richard-reid-shoe-bomber'),
  array('id' => '819','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Rikki Beadle-Blair','dob' => '0000-00-00','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Rikki Beadle-Blair (born in July 1961, in Camberwell and raised in Bermondsey, both in south London) is a British actor, director, screenwriter, playwright, singer, designer, choreographer, dancer and songwriter of British/West Indian origin. He is the artistic director of multi-media production company Team Angelica. Blair was brought up by a single mother, Monica Beadle (born 1944 in Jamaica). She and moved to Britain when she was 12.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:18:37','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'rikki-beadle-blair'),
  array('id' => '820','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Robbie Earle','dob' => '1965-01-27','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Robert Fitzgerald \\&quot;Robbie\\&quot; Earle MBE (born 27 January 1965) is an English-born Jamaican former international footballer who played as a midfielder. He played 578 league games in senior club football, scoring 136 goals.

A former youth player with Stoke City, Earle broke into the professional game with Port Vale in 1982. He spent nine years at the Burslem based club, helping the Vale to promotion out of the Fourth Division in 1982–83 and 1985–86, and out of the Third Division via the play-offs in 1989; he was later voted the club\\\'s PFA Fans\\\' Favourites. He moved on to Wimbledon in 1991, where he also spent nine years. He made nearly 300 league games for each club, scoring 77 and 59 goals respectively. He also represented Jamaica on 33 occasions between 1997 and 2000, scoring eight international goals. He appeared in the 1998 World Cup, scoring his nation\\\'s first ever goal in the finals.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:20:55','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'robbie-earle'),
  array('id' => '821','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Roots Manuva','dob' => '1972-09-08','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Rodney Hylton Smith, better known by his stage name Roots Manuva (born 8 September 1972), is an English rapper signed to Big Dada. Smith grew up around Stockwell, London, England. His parents were from a small village in Jamaica where his father was a preacher and tailor. He spent much of his early life in poverty and this and his strict Pentecostal upbringing had an influence on his music as can be heard in many of his tracks such as \\&quot;Sinny Sin Sins\\&quot; and \\&quot;Colossal Insight\\&quot;.','video' => '','image' => '','tags' => '','facebook' => '','twitter' => '','facebookfanpage' => '','twitterfanpage' => '','instagram' => '','status' => '1','admin_id' => '1','conform' => '0','modifydate' => '0000-00-00','createdate' => '2014-07-06 18:25:38','postdate' => '0000-00-00 00:00:00','rejectreason' => '','shortdesc' => NULL,'twittershortdesc' => NULL,'slug' => 'roots-manuva'),
  array('id' => '822','region_id' => '2','title' => 'Rustie Lee','dob' => '0000-00-00','kind' => 'People profile','category' => 'Others','description' => 'Rustie Lee (born 1953) is a television chef and media personality in the United Kingdom.Lee first came to public attention for her appearances during the 1980s on the morning television station TV-am.[1] Following her initial successful period as a chef on TV-am in 1983, Lee took over from Sarah Kennedy on the second incarnation of ITV show gameshow Game for a Laugh.[2]

